lindsay owens the clayman institute for gender research skip to main content standford university the clayman institute for gender research the clayman institute for gender research home programs news strategic focus events about research fellowships library media center gender news influential voices beth garfield walking away from a mortgage might make sense events no events found you are here home people lindsay owens lindsay owens graduate student sociology lindsay owens is a ph d candidate in the department of sociology at stanford university with research interests in social stratification housing debt consumption and public opinion she is also a national poverty fellow at stanford's center on poverty and inequality and a national science foundation graduate research fellow lindsay's current work examines how social and normative considerations influence consumer debt repayment how americans preferences for redistribution change in response to their changing economic circumstances and how increasing financialization of the household in recent decades has changed how and what americans consume she was contributing author to the 2011 book the great recession and her paper confidence in banks financial institutions and wall street 1971 2011 appeared in public opinion quarterly in the spring of 2012 lindsay received her ba in sociology and psychology from the university of pennsylvania in 2006 donate make a donation social links facebook twitter youtube scribd contact serra house 589 capistrano way stanford ca 94305 8640 map 650 723 1994 gender email stanford edu
